my Controller that container the form: 
import React from 'react';
import { Input } from '../../components/Input';
import { useFormContext, Controller } from 'react-hook-form';

import styles from '../styles.module.css';

const INPUTS = [
  { label: 'Firma', id: 'verzeichnis-firma' },
  { label: 'Bezeichnung', id: 'verzeichnis-bezeichnung' },
  { label: 'Zweck', id: 'verzeichnis-zweck' },
];

const Verzeichnis_Step1 = () => {
  const { control, formState } = useFormContext();

  console.log('formState: ', formState);

  return (
    <div className="card-body">
      <div className={styles.verzeichnisInputsWrapper}>
        {INPUTS.map((input) => (
          <Controller
            key={input.id}
            control={control}
            name={`step1.${input.label.toLowerCase()}`}
            rules={{ required: true }}
            defaultValue=""
            render={({ field }) => (
              <Input
                {...input}
                {...field}
                value={field.value}
                onChange={field.onChange}
                error={formState.errors[input.label.toLowerCase()]}
              />
            )}
          />
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  );
};

export { Verzeichnis_Step1 };


my form container: 

import React, { useContext, useState } from 'react';
import Navbar from '../components/Navbar';
import AuthContext from '../context/AuthProvider';
import { useNavigate } from 'react-router-dom';
import VerzeichnisProzesse from './components/VerzeichnisProzesse';

import VerzeichnisStart from './components/VerzeichnisStart';
import { VerzeichnisFormular } from './components/VerzeichnisFormular';
import { useForm, FormProvider } from 'react-hook-form';

const generateUniqueId = () => {
  return Math.random().toString(36).substr(2, 6).toUpperCase();
};

const Verzeichnis = () => {
  const { auth, setToken } = useContext(AuthContext);
  const navigate = useNavigate();
  const [activeStep, setActiveStep] = useState(0);

  const handleNext = () => {
    setActiveStep((prevStep) => prevStep + 1);
  };

  const handleBack = () => {
    setActiveStep((prevStep) => prevStep - 1);
  };

  const methods = useForm({ mode: 'onChange' });

  const onSubmit = (data) => {
    const formattedData = { ...data, id: generateUniqueId() };
    if (activeStep === 9) {
      const prevData = JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem('verzeichnisData'));
      const newData = prevData ? [formattedData, ...prevData] : [formattedData];

      localStorage.setItem('verzeichnisData', JSON.stringify(newData));
      navigate('/VerzeichnisOverview');
    }
    console.log(data);
  };

  console.log('formValues: ', methods.getValues());

  return (
    <div className="wrapper">
      <div id="content">
        <div className="container">
          <div className="row topmargin100">
            <div className="col-md-2"></div>
            <div className="card col-md-8">
              <FormProvider {...methods}>
                <form onSubmit={methods.handleSubmit(onSubmit)}>
                  {activeStep === 0 && <VerzeichnisStart next={handleNext} />}
                  {activeStep === 1 && (
                    <VerzeichnisProzesse next={handleNext} back={handleBack} />
                  )}
                  {activeStep > 1 && (
                    <VerzeichnisFormular
                      activeStep={activeStep}
                      next={handleNext}
                      back={handleBack}
                    />
                  )}
                </form>
              </FormProvider>
            </div>
            <div className="col-md-2"></div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
};

export default Verzeichnis;



why is validation rules not working? In this case the 'required' is not working. I can submit the form without the fields being filled in

In that case, you can try changing the mode of the useForm hook to 'onSubmit'. This will validate the entire form when the submit button is clicked, instead of validating each field on change or blur. 

To set the onSubmit mode, pass the mode option to the useForm() function:

```
const methods = useForm({ mode: 'onSubmit' });
```

This will make the validation rules work as expected, but keep in mind that the validation error messages will not appear until the submit button is clicked. 

You can also try logging the errors object in the onSubmit function to see if there are any validation errors that are not being displayed:

```
const onSubmit = (data) => {
    const formattedData = { ...data, id: generateUniqueId() };
    if (activeStep === 9) {
      const prevData = JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem('verzeichnisData'));
      const newData = prevData ? [formattedData, ...prevData] : [formattedData];

      localStorage.setItem('verzeichnisData', JSON.stringify(newData));
      navigate('/VerzeichnisOverview');
    }
    console.log(methods.errors); // Log the validation errors
};
```

This will help you debug the issue and ensure that the validation rules are correctly defined.

In that case, you can keep the 'onChange' mode for the useForm hook. 

To make sure the validation rules work correctly with the controlled Input component, you can add the 'onChange' and 'onBlur' event handlers to the Input component:

```
const Input = React.forwardRef(
  ({ label, type = 'text', className, value, onChange, onBlur, error, name }, ref) => {
    return (
      <FormField error={error}>
        <div className={styles.inputWrapper}>
          {label && (
            <label
              htmlFor={name}
              className={styles.inputLabel}
              style={{ marginBottom: 0 }}
            >
              {label}
            </label>
          )}
          <input
            type={type}
            className={`form-control morphfield ${styles.input} ${className}`}
            id={name}
            value={value}
            onChange={onChange}
            onBlur={onBlur} // Add onBlur event handler
            ref={ref}
          />
        </div>
      </FormField>
    );
  }
);
```

Then, in the Controller component, add the 'onBlur' event handler to the render function:

```
<Controller
  key={input.id}
  control={control}
  name={`step1.${input.label.toLowerCase()}`}
  rules={{ required: true }}
  defaultValue=""
  render={({ field }) => (
    <Input
      {...input}
      {...field}
      error={formState.errors[input.label.toLowerCase()]}
      onBlur={field.onBlur} // Add onBlur event handler
    />
  )}
/>
```

This will ensure that the validation rules are triggered both on change and blur events for the input fields, and will update the form data and validation accordingly.

If adding the 'onBlur' event handler to the Input component and Controller component didn't help, there might be an issue with the way the name of the input field is defined in the Controller component.

Make sure that the name property in the Controller component matches the name of the input field in the Input component, and that it is correctly formatted according to the React Hook Form guidelines. 

For example, if the input field name is 'Firma', the name property in the Controller component should be:

```
name={`step1.firma`}
```

Also, make sure that the rules property in the Controller component is correctly defined. In this case, since you're using the 'required' rule, make sure to add it to the rules object and set it to true, like this:

```
rules={{ required: true }}
```

If the name and rules properties are correctly defined, and the 'onBlur' event handler is added to the Input component, the validation rules should work as expected. If you're still having trouble, try logging the errors object in the onSubmit function to see if there are any validation errors that are not being displayed:

```
const onSubmit = (data) => {
  // ...
  console.log(methods.errors); // Log the validation errors
};
```

This can help you debug the issue and ensure that the validation rules are correctly defined.

If the errors object is empty, it means that the form validation is not working correctly. 

One possible reason for this could be that the rules are not being correctly passed to the Input component. Make sure that you're passing the rules object to the Controller component, like this:

```
<Controller
  key={input.id}
  control={control}
  name={`step1.${input.label.toLowerCase()}`}
  rules={{ required: true }}
  defaultValue=""
  render={({ field }) => (
    <Input
      {...input}
      {...field}
      error={formState.errors[input.label.toLowerCase()]}
      onBlur={field.onBlur}
    />
  )}
/>
```

Another possible reason could be that there's an issue with the FormField component that you're using to wrap the Input component. Make sure that this component is correctly handling the error prop and displaying the error message, like this:

```
const FormField = ({ children, error }) => {
  return (
    <div>
      {children}
      {error && (
        <div className={styles.errorMessage}>
          {error.message || 'This field is required'}
        </div>
      )}
    </div>
  );
};
```

If neither of these solutions work, try checking the version of the react-hook-form package that you're using, and make sure that it's up-to-date. If you're still having trouble, posting more of your code or sharing a CodeSandbox example could help in debugging the issue.

If passing the rules object to the Controller component and ensuring that the FormField component is correctly handling the error prop didn't help, try checking the rest of your code to see if there's anything else that could be causing the issue.

One possible reason could be that the useForm hook is not being used correctly. Make sure that you're wrapping your form components within the FormProvider component, like this:

```
<FormProvider {...methods}>
  <form onSubmit={methods.handleSubmit(onSubmit)}>
    // Form components go here
  </form>
</FormProvider>
```

Also, make sure that the useForm hook methods are being correctly used in the Input and Controller components. You can check if the value and error values are being correctly passed to the Input component by logging them:

```
