```

This can help you debug the issue and see if the form state is being correctly updated with the validation errors, or if there's something else happening that could be causing the issue.

If the errors object inside formState is always an empty object, it means that no validation errors are being registered by the form. 

One possible reason for this could be that the validation rules are not being correctly defined in the rules object of the Controller component. You can try adding a custom error message to the required validation rule, like this:

```
<Controller
  key={input.id}
  control={control}
  name={`step1.${input.label.toLowerCase()}`}
  rules={{ required: 'This field is required' }} // Add custom error message
  defaultValue=""
  render={({ field }) => (
    <Input
      {...input}
      {...field}
      error={formState.errors[input.label.toLowerCase()]}
      onBlur={field.onBlur}
    />
  )}
/>
```

Make sure to properly define the validation rules for each input field in the rules object, according to the react-hook-form documentation.

If adding a custom error message to the required validation rule didn't work, try wrapping your form components inside the Form component instead of the FormProvider component. The Form component is a higher-level component that also provides form-related functions and variables to children components. You can use it instead of the FormProvider component like this:

```
import { useForm } from 'react-hook-form';

const Verzeichnis_Step1 = () => {
  const { register, handleSubmit, formState } = useForm({ mode: 'onChange' });

  const onSubmit = (data) => {
    console.log('form data:', data);
    console.log('form errors:', formState.errors);
  };

  return (
    <div className="card-body">
      <form onSubmit={handleSubmit(onSubmit)}>
        <div className={styles.verzeichnisInputsWrapper}>
          {INPUTS.map((input) => (
            <div key={input.id} className={styles.inputContainer}>
              <label htmlFor={input.id}>{input.label}</label>
              <input
                id={input.id}
                type="text"
                className={`${styles.input} ${
                  formState.errors[input.id] ? styles.error : ''
                }`}
                {...register(input.id, { required: true })}
              />
              {formState.errors[input.id] && (
                <p className={styles.errorMessage}>
                  {formState.errors[input.id].message}
                </p>
              )}
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
        <button type="submit">Submit</button>
      </form>
    </div>
  );
};
```

This can help you debug the issue and ensure that the validation rules are being correctly defined for each input field.

If the issue could be related to nested field names, you can try using the different register names for the nested input fields. 

For example, if you have a field named 'Firma' and it's inside the 'step1' object, the register name for this field could be `register("step1.firma", { required: true })`. 

